[Student "S"]
{North's 2\C cue-bid shows a limit-raise or better in \Ss. South is to play 4\S. West leads the \C2. East plays the \CK.

Losers:   \S=0  \H=2  \D=1  \C=1  Total = 4

You have one loser too many. If West holds either the \HA or the \DK this will be an easy contract, but East opened the bidding so he probably has most of the high cards. It does look like West holds the \CQ based on his low lead and East's play to trick one.

Having gone through that thought process what is your Plan?

You will need to discard a loser on dummy's fourth \D, but you must do so without ever letting West gain the lead since West is the defender who can lead through dummy's \HK. And the only card that West can get the lead with is the \CQ.

Hold-ups are usually used in notrump hands, but here you use one to prevent the Danger Hand from gaining the lead. Let East have the \CK. He cannot play a red card without helping you so he will surely play another \C. 

Pull trumps in two rounds. Then play the \D10 and let it ride.

East will win this but he is helpless. Whatever he plays you will be able to discard a \H loser on dummy's \D.

The purpose of the hold-up play is to cut communications between the two defenders. Here you knew you would lose exactly one \C trick so you chose to lose it to East, the Safe Hand.

If you had taken the first \C trick East would have won your later \D finesse, put his partner on lead with the \CQ and then swallowed up your \HK.

Of course if West had been clever enough to lead a \H originally this Deal wouldn't be here.}
[Play "W"]C2

