[Student "S"]
{South is to play 3NT. West leads the \HK. East plays the \H6.

Winners:   \S=3  \H=1  \D=1  \C=3  Total = 8

You just need one more winner and it could come from the \D suit if it happens to split 3-3. But you have another possibility. Suppose you let West hold the first trick and he decides to play another \H? You would have two \H winners.

This isn't a true hold-up play although it does look like one. This play has the rather fancy name of Bath Coup, (named from Bath, England). Presumably West has led from \H K Q 10 9 5 and East has played his singleton \H6. If West realizes that East has played his lowest card he will take that as a discouraging signal and will play a different suit. So you throw out your \H7 rather than the \H3. Now West may think that East is encouraging him to continue, just what you want.

Sometimes it works, sometimes it doesn't.

I sure hope that when you play this hand West falls for your Bath Coup.

Because if he doesn't you're going to have to end-play him.

Do you see how that might happen?}
[Play "W"]HK

